b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe29056.htm)  [Next](sbe29058.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n[Buy this Book at\nAmazon.com](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1421228750/internetsacredte)\n\n* * *\n\n_The Grihya Sutras, Part 1 (SBE29)_ , by Hermann Oldenberg, [1886], at sacred-\ntexts.com\n\n* * *\n\n### KHA _N_ _D_ A 9.\n\n1 1. 'May the noisy (goddesses) keep you away from slaughtering hosts. May the\nentire share, O cows, that belongs to this lord of cows, suffer no harm among\nyou\xc2\x97(and)\n\n'May Pushan go after our cows' (Rig-veda VI, 54, 5)\xc2\x97this he shall speak over\nthe cows when they go away (to their pasture-grounds).\n\n2\\. 'May Pushan hold' (Rig-veda VI, 54, 10), when they run about.\n\n3\\. 'May they whose udder with its four holes is full of sweet and ghee, be\nmilk-givers to us; (may they be) many in our stable, rich in ghee'\xc2\x97and, 'The\ncows have come' (Rig-veda VI, 28), when they have come back.\n\n4\\. The last (verse) when he puts them in (into the stable).\n\n5\\. The hymn, 'Refreshing wind' (Rig-veda X, 169), (he recites over the cows),\nwhen they are gone into the stable.\n\n* * *\n\n### Footnotes\n\n[99:1](sbe29057.htm#fr_218) 9, 1. The noisy ones are the winds; comp. the\npassage of _S_ a\xe1\xb9\x85khayana- _S_ rauta-sutra, quoted p. 144 of the German\nedition.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: III, 10](sbe29058.htm)\n\n"